postcontent: Manufactured in 1985. Shoots flawless and never had any problems.  What I used for my every day carry until I recently bought a glock 26 .45 to carry.  The CZ82 is by far the best of its makerov variants.  Was a military/Czech police sidearm from 1983 to 1994.  The first of its kind to have polygonal rifling and a fixed barrel for improved accuracy and less blowback. Breaks down in seconds for the easiest cleaning I've ever had to do. title: For Sale:  Kimber BPTen II with extras
postcontent:
Selling my used Kimber BP Ten II. Up front the only issue with the gun is the original *plastic* grip safety snapped in two following a fall off a coffee table. Because no grip safeties exist *anywhere* for this gun, I had to modify a Caspian Arms .220 radius to fit and restore function. To that end the gun functions great and looks proper but this is not an original part. Neither is the threaded 5.5" Stainless Storm Lake Barrel and Wolf 25 lb spring I installed. .578x28" thread for a suppressor or brake and is covered with a Stainless steel thread protector. The heavy spring eliminates recoil. This has been my carry gun for a long time and fires and functions wonderfully. Will include two Mec-gar 13 round magazines and a modified Para 20 rounder. This gun is a great gun for a shooter and 13 rounds of .45 ACP in a 1911 full size is a lot of firepower. Pricing it low due to the modified grip safety. Otherwise the gun is 8/10, some cosmetic holster wear and use wear on the slide and moving parts but the slide and barrel are pretty tight. If you have or know someone with a proper .250" radius hi-cap grip safety you can easily have a great looking and solidly functioning shooter. About 200 rounds in the new barrel and 700 rounds through the gun overall. Mostly 230 grain Winchester ball and hydrashoks. Price is firm, Local sales only, must have valid AZ drivers license and because it's a handgun I'd also prefer to sell only to CCW holders. Must also be willing to sign a transfer of ownership form. 


*** I provided a few pictures*** I have more pictures of the replacement grip safety upon request. Really needs a .250" out of a Charles Daly, BUL M-5 or similar gun.

The raised cheek piece helps to direct recoil into the shoulder area and quickly puts the shooter's line of sight in alignment with the scope

title: For Sale:  METROPLEX MILITARY CHARITABLE TRUST is seeking donations
postcontent:
Dear Sir, my name is Ray, I am a US Marine (1978-1984) and an active member of the Metroplex Marines here in North Texas. We are part of the METROPLEX MILITARY CHARITABLE TRUST, a 501c3 with a mission to help local military personnel, regular, reserve and retired, and to military support charities and volunteer organizations. 

We are about to start an on-line auction in an effort to raise moneys for our fellow service men/women and their families. I am writing you today to ask for donations in the way of firearms and related firearms products, which we will auction off in the coming months. 

100% of the moneys we raise goes to the effort, understand that every member of the Metroplex Marines/METROPLEX MILITARY CHARITABLE TRUST is a volunteer, no one is paid and we don’t keep any of the moneys we raise, period!

I have enclosed some information on the METROPLEX MILITARY CHARITABLE TRUST as well as a link to our website for your review and consideration. http://www.metroplexmarines.org/

I hope we can count on your support for our up coming on-line auction. Please consider donating some of your firearms as well as ammo and other related products and services to our cause. All of your donations are fully tax deductible.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
METROPLEX MILITARY CHARITABLE TRUST 
3510 Rankin
Dallas, Texas 75205
Fax REDACTED
REDACTED

STATEMENT OF PURPOSE
March 19, 2014

The MMCT is a 501 (c) (3) charity and was started in 1990 in Dallas, TX.  Its mission is to provide economic support to local military personnel, regular, reserve and retired, and to military support charities and volunteer organizations.  Such assistance has been as varied as underwriting every local  USMC Toys For Tots Campaign since 1991; providing individual grants to individual returning reservists, who have lost their jobs and/or homes to; making grants to JRB Carswell Guard & Reserve Associations and DFW Marine/Navy Families.  Its longest and largest effort has been to provide direct support to families of amputee, PTSD, and brain-injured OIF & OEF Vets as well as the Vets themselves through the North Texas VA Warrior Patient Shuttle service since September 2007 and the official active duty (United States Marine Corps and Navy Corpsman) in Quantico, VA The Official Wounded Warrior Regiment covering costs not taken care of by the DOD, USMC JROTC High School Programs, ReserveAid and Joe Foss Institute.

In 2007 there were about 1300 VA OIF and OEF outpatients registered using three major VA medical facilities in northeast Texas-The Bonham VA Medical Center, The Ft Worth VA Outpatient Clinic, and The Dallas VA PolyTrauma Unit in Oak Cliff, Dallas.  Of those 1300 patients 100 PTSD were outpatients at Ft Worth, while 65 PTSD veterans reported to the PolyTrauma Unit.  65% of the outpatients at the PolyTrauma unit also had a brain injury.   

In 2009 the Veterans Resource Center was set up as a 501 (c) (3) originally named Homeless Veterans Services of Dallas.  We currently provide all branches of the military, 6,000 Veterans in 2013, ranging from Daycare and female resources resulting in employment, education, healthcare, transportation and traditional housing.

The MMCT underwrites the expenses of the shuttle service which is manned entirely by volunteers.  Three wheelchair converted Dodge Caravan’s were originally purchased, and their respective fuel, insurance, and maintenance expenses were underwritten by the MMCT by way of a Triad Fund Grant of about $234,000, which grant was renewed for about $130,000 in 2010.  1564 patient’s trips were provided from each patient’s home to the relevant North Texas VA facility for treatment, and back home from April 1, 2011 through January 30, 2012.  1564 of these same patient’s trips were provided from April 1, 2011 through January 30, 2012.  Additional vans have been donated to this effort, one by Harriet Miers, former White House Counsel for President George W. Bush, and first female president for State of Texas Bar Association.   MMCT also underwrites the expenses for those vans.

The MMCT does not charge anyone for its services and all of our labor is provided at no costs to MMCT, except CPA audit and Tax return preparation is totally volunteered.  The CPA cost was around $2,500.  The only other G & A expense was the cost of the Directors and Officers Liability insurance of $2,140 (2yr premium).
